## 8. Permitted Purposes (free)

Only the following are free permitted purposes. All other use requires an
active **Commercial License** under Section 9.

### 8.1 Personal and Hobby

Individual personal use for private entertainment, hobby projects, amateur
pursuits, personal study, or unpaid learning, without use for the benefit of a
company that fails Section 8.2, is a permitted purpose.

### 8.2 Small Business (PolyForm thresholds)

Use of the software for the benefit of your company is use for a permitted
purpose **only if** your company has fewer than **100** total individuals
working as employees and independent contractors, **and** less than
**1,000,000 USD (2019)** total revenue in the prior tax year. Adjust this
revenue threshold for inflation according to the United States Bureau of Labor
Statistics' consumer price index for all urban consumers, U.S. city average,
for all items, not seasonally adjusted, with 1982–1984=100 reference base.

If your company exceeds either threshold, Section 8.2 no longer applies, and
continued use for the benefit of your company requires Section 9.

## 9. Commercial License (mandatory above Small Business)

### 9.1 When required

If you (or your company) want to use the software for the benefit of a company
that does **not** qualify under Section 8.2 — including because it meets or
exceeds the employee/contractor count or revenue threshold — you **must**
obtain and maintain an active Commercial License **before** such use (or
immediately upon ceasing to qualify, and in any event within 14 days).

Use without an active Commercial License when Section 9 applies is a
**material breach**. Your copyright and patent licenses for that use end, and
the licensor may seek injunctive relief, unpaid fees, and other remedies.

### 9.2 Fees — $200 USD per month

The Commercial License fee is **two hundred United States dollars (USD $200)
per calendar month**, paid **in advance**, **directly to the creator /
licensor**: Alexander James Patton (AJpro774).

Payment must be arranged with the licensor (for example via the contact method
published on the official Juni / Juno GitHub repository or official site). The
licensor may specify accepted payment methods. Fees are non-refundable except
as required by law.

An active Commercial License means the applicable month is paid and the
licensor has not terminated the Commercial License for breach.

### 9.3 What the Commercial License covers

While active, the Commercial License permits use of the software for the
benefit of your company (including internal tooling and commercial product
development with Juni), subject to the rest of these terms. It does **not**
transfer ownership of the software, grant trademark rights, or allow you to
rebrand or resell the Juni IDE/compiler as a competing product or SaaS without
a separate written agreement.

### 9.4 Suspension and termination for non-payment

If payment lapses, the Commercial License ends at the end of the last paid
month. Continued Commercial-License-required use after that date is
unauthorized. The licensor may terminate the Commercial License immediately for
material breach.

## 10. Game and Project Export Exception

You retain ownership of projects, games, assets, and content you create with
the software (“Your Content”).

You may distribute Your Content, including commercially, and you may include
with Your Content only the portions of the Juni runtime and supporting files
that the software’s normal export / publish features emit for running Your
Content (for example `juni export-web` output), provided that:

1. You do not present the Juni IDE, compiler, or language tooling as your
   product
2. You do not remove Required Notice lines from those runtime files where they
   appear
3. You do not use this exception to redistribute the IDE, compiler, source
   tree, or a competing toolchain

Shipping Your Content under this exception does not by itself satisfy Section
9 if your company otherwise must hold a Commercial License to use the software
in development.

